This is just a reminder that beginning tomorrow, Monday September 14th the Edison Local School District will be offering free breakfast and lunch to all student in grades PK-12 until December 18, 2020.

Also, any students who are remote or on ECAT can pick up breakfast and lunch at John Gregg and Stanton Elementary Monday through Friday from 10:30 a.m. to 11:00 a.m. Someone will be at the main entrance at John Gregg and at the lobby doors located by the cemetery at Stanton. There will not be a pick location at Edison High School.

Any questions feel free to reach out to your child’s building principal or call Mrs. Smuck at (740) 282-0065 extension 1114.

post_text:
Edison High School is pleased to announce Shane O’Brien as the August Teacher of the Month. Coach O’Brien is a 2012 graduate of Edison High School and continued his football career at Mount Union University.

Coach O’Brien graduated from West Liberty University in 2016 with a BS in Exercise Physiology. Coach O'Brien teaches weightlifting and serves as the head football coach. This is Coach O’Brien’s third season at the helm for the Wildcats after serving as an assistant coach for the past four years under Coach Stickles and Coach Moses. Coach was able to lead the Wildcats to a season-opening 31-19 victory over rival Toronto this week.

Coach O’Brien has also coached both track and wrestling during his time here at EHS.

Coach is the son of Dave and Jenney O’Brien. Coach O’Brien is dating head cheerleading coach Madison Brown and enjoys health and fitness.

post_text:
Mr. Beattie's One Call Message from Monday:

I just wanted to take this opportunity to give a shoutout to the students and parents for a great first day of school. We appreciate the students for following the face mask order and adhering to
the protocol.

I also want to ask that you be patient over the next several days as we figure out the most optimal way to accomplish our daily routines in opening a new school year and adding in the new protocols with temperature and symptom checks.

You may be experiencing buses being a little later than scheduled,
we will be working hard this week to get those times back to as close to normal.

As mentioned Sunday’s one call, the high school doors do not open until 7:35 a.m. and the doors at John Gregg and Stanton don’t open until 8:40 a.m. Please don’t drop your child off before these times or they will have to wait outside for the doors to open.

Please remember to charge your device tonight and bring your charger to school tomorrow.

Thanks again students for doing your part today. Let’s do it 169 more times.

Good Evening, the Edison Local School District will have Open House for students on Wednesday, August 26th and Thursday, August 27th.

On Wednesday, August 26th Open House for grades 1, 3, 5, 7, 9 and 11 will be held and grades 2, 4, 6, 8, 10 and 12 will be on Thursday, August 27th.

For both evenings, students whose last name begins will A-L will attend from 4:00 to 5:15 and students whose last name begins with M-Z will attend from 5:45 to 7:00.

There will be presentations on how to log in on several applications that will be used on your chrome book. You need to be there at the start of the meeting to receive the full presentation.

Students in grades 8 through 12 need to bring their device with them to the Open House. Students in grades PK-7 will receive their device at Open House.

Bus routes and times will be available in each building.

We are asking that only one parent and the student attend Open House due to space restrictions.

If you have a conflict with Open House please reach out directly to your child’s building principal to seek a resolution.

Jefferson County Fair Official
July 28 at 10:06 PM ·

ATTENTION: 2020 HIGH SCHOOL GRADUATES
Attached to this post is the application for the Mackenzie Smith Memorial Livestock Scholarship Fund. The Mackenzie Smith Memorial Livestock Scholarship Fund was established by Mackenzie's Jefferson County Fair friends and family to honor her memory. The fund will be awarding a scholarship to one Jefferson County Jr. Fair Exhibitor for the 2020 - 2021 college term. To be eligible to receive this scholarship, applicants must be a 2020 high school graduate, must have exhibited market livestock at the Jefferson County Jr. Fair for at least three consecutive years, have a cumulative GPA of 3.0 or higher and be furthering their education past high school graduation.
Please see the application for additional details.
If you would like an application emailed to you, please message this page.

The Edison High School Employee of the Month for June is Chris Springer.

Chris has been cook at E.H.S. and has been working for the food service department for four years.

She is blessed to be a mom to three beautiful young adults, all of which are Edison graduates.

Chris wants to give a shout-out to our students for making her job fun and rewarding, and also to thank the Edison staff and her co-workers for always making her feel welcomed and appreciated.

Chris also wanted to say good luck to our seniors, wish everyone in Edison Nation a happy and healthy summer, and say "GO CATS!"

I have reached out to all the students to send me extra pictures for the yearbook. Some have responded, but I would love to have more.

Pictures of your Commencement/Graduation celebrations with friends and family

Spring Sports Senior Parents--I would like any pictures that you have of them playing their sports throughout the years

So every Class of 2020 parent, please pick out a few of your favorite pictures and email them to james.evans@edisonwildcats.org Email is best because the resolution needed for the yearbook pages doesn't work with Facebook messenger.

Everyone else, please like share and tag as many parents as possible!

post_text:
You may pick up you diplomas at the HS on Tuesday-Thursday from 8:00 AM to 3:00 PM. The schools will be closed on Mondays and Fridays this summer.
I would also like you to send in pictures of your private commencement celebrations for me to include in the yearbook. These might be pictures of events you held with your families or things that you did with your friends. I want to be abe to capture the unique and different ways that you were able to celebrate your achievements in the absence of a traditional commencement ceremony.
I would also like to have pictures of you and your classmates through the years. I would love for these pictures to be as class of 2020 centric as possible. Try to limit the number of students from other grades in the picture. Some are okay, but as many of you in the pictures as possible. These can be ANY pictures from grade school all the way up through high school and they can be from outside school as well. Just make sure that all of the pictures are appropriate and as high quality as possible. (Cell Phone Photos usually work.)

Thanks,
Mr. Evans

The Edison High School Employee of the month for May is Kari Speedy.

Kari is a graduate of Edison High School, and her daughter, Karissa Speedy, will be graduating 2021. Kari has been an employee with Edison in the kitchen for three years. She is so happy to work with such a wonderful staff, and serving the kids is the highlight of her day.

Kari wanted to make sure she gave one last shout out to the Class of 2020, congratulations and good luck!

post_text: More Wildcat talent performing “Songs of Hope”!
shared_text:
Bobbyjon Bauman is with Raymond Szypulski and 10 others.
May 10 at 7:52 PM ·

Melia Forrester and Jt Pipo will be the featured artists tomorrow (Monday) Evening for the “Sycamore Sings! Songs of Hope” Facebook “Live” Concert Series. Melia graduated from Edison in 2012 and Franciscan University in 2016. She has been playing the piano since the 2nd grade and has been under the tutelage of Edison Choir Director Dani Carroll since the 7th grade and has had the privilege of using her piano skills by performing in Edison’s Orchestra for years. Jt is a sophomore at Edison and has performed in band, choir and theater under Dani Carroll. He’s played alongside Melia in a few musicals and just got accepted into the All Ohio State Fair Band this summer. These two will be treating you to some of their favorite broadway and Disney tunes! I would encourage Wildcat Nation😺 and everyone else to tune in for this inspiring brother sister duo tomorrow night for a positive, uplifting performance that will truly uplift your heart!❤️

post_text: Another Edison Nation talent to tune into!
shared_text:
Bobbyjon Bauman is with Victoria Collins and 10 others.
May 7 at 7:52 PM ·

I initially saw Amelia Collopy at the Stanton Elementary talent show as a 5th grader and she had me in tears as she sang “How Great Thou Art” so beautifully that it felt like you were transported to heaven. The video of that song went on to garner 16,000 views on Facebook and this young lady is even better now with a voice that is powerful and seasoned well beyond her years. She was the winner of the Mingo Idol competition last year and also was the 2018 Valleys Got Talent Soloist Runner Up as an 11 year old! She is a product of the stellar Edison School district that has produced a number of highly skilled vocalists who have already performed for the Sycamore Sings! Songs of Hope. Amelia will be featured on Facebook “Live” from 7-7:15 PM Friday on her mom’s Facebook page and my page. I strongly encourage Edison Nation😺 to support Amelia as well as everyone else who would like to hear a young vocal star give a performance for the ages!!!⭐️🌟💫

Update from Mr. Beattie:

Good Evening,
If you did not pick up your packet this evening, our bus driver’s will be delivering tomorrow morning, Tuesday, May 5th. They will deliver from 9:00 till 12:00.

Please keep an eye out for the bus. If you have completed work to turn in you can give it to them when they drop off the new packets.
If the packets are undeliverable, the State Highway Patrol will deliver on Wednesday, May 6th between the times of 9:00 and noon.

Are you interested in earning extra Cash this Summer? If you are between the ages of 16-24 and meet income guidelines the Jefferson County CAC is offering the Summer Youth Program. Qualifying participants will earn a wage of $9.00 per hour. You can visit www.ohiomeansjobsjeffersoncounty.com and complete the application.

shared_text:

Tomorrow night (Monday) The Valley’s Got Talent Vocal Soloist Runner Up Leila Cable of Stanton Elementary School will be performing for the “Sycamore Sings: Songs of Hope” Online Concert Series from 7:00-7:15 pm. She landed the starring role as “Sherlock Holmes” in “The Enchanted Bookshop” Musical at Stanton Elementary. This little 11 yr. old will melt your heart with her grace filled soaring vocals that are as sweet as honey. She wowed the crowd with her performance of the Laura Story song “Blessings” taking home one of the top prizes ever at the VGT for her age (only 10 at the time). I would especially encourage Wildcat nation😺to tune in and support Leila as well as anyone else that would like to have their heart uplifted by this phenomenally talented young lady. To view the show go to the Facebook page of Dawn Bailey-Cable or Bobbyjon Bauman at 7:00 PM on Friday. I promise that this is one you don’t want to miss!!!

post_text:
Mr. Beattie’s Covid-19 Update:

Good Afternoon, just a short brief update today to remind students and parents of upcoming events
Students who are completing online lessons are required to have all lessons completed by 3:00 p.m. today.

Students who have completed paper packets are required to turn in paper packets on Monday, May 4th when they come to pick up the next set of lessons. All buildings will be open on Monday from 9:00 to 11:00 and 5:00 to 6:00.

Preschool registration packets for preschool students and any new kindergarten student enrolling for the first time can pick up a registration packet on Monday, May 4th from 9:00 a.m. to 11:00 a.m. and 5:00 p.m. to 6:00 p.m. If you are unable to get the registration packet on these days, you can call John Gregg or Stanton on Wednesday’s from 8:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m. to request a registration packet.

As always please stay safe and healthy as we begin to slowly get back to some normal activities.

post_text:
EHS update:

Good Afternoon Wildcats! Tomorrow, May 4, is Paper Packet Day at the High School. You can pick up your new paper packets and drop off your completed paper packets at Edison High School tomorrow between 9 AM and 11 AM and 5 PM and 6 PM.

If you have an existing tech issue with our Help Desk, and have been in contact with Ms. Rachel and Mr. Tyler, we may have a repaired or loaner laptop at the high school for you to exchange tomorrow as well.

Please remember, you only need to come to the high school if you are a student who has elected to complete a paper packet, or you have an existing tech issue with Mrs. Rachel or Mr. Tyler and they have told you they have an exchange at the high school.

Remember to follow all social distancing guidelines and to stay six feet apart at all times. Please continue to demonstrate the Wildcat Way in our communities! Be Respectful, Be Responsible, and BE SAFE! GO CATS.

Edison Nation,

One of our Edison families could use your help! Nic (2008) and Autumn (2009) Reese's son Gabriel was recently diagnosed with Hunter's Syndrome, which is a very rare metabolic disorder that can affect the lungs, heart, joints, connective tissue, brain, and nervous system.

Current treatment for Hunter Syndrome can run up to $500,000 per year.

The family has a GoFundMe page set up which I will post below. Any donations are appreciated as are your thoughts and prayers for Gabriel!

https://www.gofundme.com/f/gabriel039s-fight-against-mps?utm_source=customer&utm_medium=copy_link-tip&utm_campaign=p_cp+share-sheet&fbclid=IwAR2f3n1Fj1vuV-5cUPy_FVZsy0BKyIbCenNuljvYCdANVxO_-_MIZjc5O8M

post_text:
Due to provisions in the Stay-at-Home order that was extended yesterday which prohibit parades and other outside gatherings, we have been forced to modify our Drive-In Senior Walk planned for Friday, May the 8th.

Any questions about this change can be addressed to Mr. Beattie at 740-282-0065 at Ext. 1104. If he is not in the office these calls will be forwarded.

The seniors will be getting an email Monday morning announcing new plans for a virtual Senior Walk, which will occur in small groups on May 8th and be put into video form and broadcast via Facebook on Sunday, May 10.

The Senior will take their "Last Walk" through the halls of Edison for all to enjoy in the comfort and safety of their homes.

Thank you for bearing with us through this unprecedented time as we work hard to provide memorable and meaningful experiences for the Class of 2020.

Carter Matthew Montgomery is the son of Scott and Tiffany Montgomery of Steubenville. Carter finishes his career at Edison High School with a 4.0 GPA and is a Valedictorian of the Class of 2020. During his time at Edison, Carter played soccer for four years and was the kicker on the football team his sophomore through senior seasons. Carter was a four-year member of the Edison High School Chapter of the National Beta Club, was a member of the Student Council and an office aide his junior year and competed on the Academic Competition Team as a senior. Carter was named 1st team all Eastern District and All OVAC in soccer and was honored as a 2nd team All Easter District selection in football as well. Carter is also serving as Senior Class President this year. Carter plans to attend West Liberty University and major in Human Biology.

post_text:
May is Senior Month in Edison Nation!

Beginning this evening starting at 6:00pm with the release of our Top Ten and Commencement Speaker, each day we will be honoring the Class of 2020. We will release the top ten at 5-minute increments starting with the commencement speaker and working the way up to our Valedictorians.

Each member of the Class should be receiving a letter outlining the plans for our major senior events, including commencement. That list will be posted here after our Seniors have had a chance to receive it and look over it first.

We have several exciting events planned as well as daily senior spotlights that will be posted at Noon, 2:00, 4:00 and 6:00pm each day.

Every Wednesday, we will highlight Seniors that have committed to being Enrolled, Enlisted, or Employed in the fall as well.

We need Edison Nation to come together like never before to honor the Class of 2020!

Edison Nation,

Tune in to listen to a Junior Gracie Phillips!
shared_text:
Bobbyjon Bauman is with Victoria Collins and 14 others.
April 30 at 7:58 PM ·

2X Valley’s Got Talent finalist Gracie Phillips will be performing for the “Sycamore Sings: Songs of Hope” Online Concert Series Friday (5/1) from 7:00-7:15 pm. She had the starring role as “Jane” in “Tarzan: The Musical” at Edison HS and gave a performance for the ages😱. She sings beautiful soul stirring hymns, show tunes, country and inspiring Contemporary Christian songs. I’ve taught Gracie a number of times while subbing at Edison and have found her to be not only an able scholar but an all around good girl who is a true asset to her local school. She is a part of the Edison Choral program under the tutelage of Master Choir Instructor Dani Carroll who blew up the internet a few weeks ago with her Sycamore Facebook "live" performance with over 1,300 views. I would especially encourage Wildcat nation😺to tune in and support Gracie as well as anyone else that would like to have their heart uplifted by this phenomenally talented young lady.🎤🎼🙌🏻 To view the show go to the Facebook page of Gracie Phillips or Bobbyjon Bauman at 7:00 PM on Friday.

Update from Mr. Beattie:

Good Evening, this is a clarification from the one call that was sent out on Sunday.

Students who are completing online lessons are required to have all lessons completed by 3:00 p.m. on Sunday, May 3rd.

Students who have completed paper packets are required to turn in paper packets on Monday, May 4th when they come to pick up the next set of lessons.

Preschool registration packets for preschool students and any new kindergarten student enrolling for the first time can pick up a registration packet on Friday, May 1st from 9:00 a.m. to 11:00 a.m. and also on Monday, May 4th from 9:00 a.m. to 11:00 a.m. and 5:00 p.m. to 6:00 p.m. If you are unable to get the registration packet on these days, you can call John Gregg or Stanton on Wednesday’s from 8:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m. to request a registration packet.

As always please stay safe and healthy as we begin to slowly get back to some normal activities.

#SHAREYOURLIGHT

Share a photo of your lit candle to help us come together for a "Virtual Candlelight Vigil" and to spread awareness of those that are still out there suffering in silence, without a voice. The Edison Highschool Cheerleaders need your help spreading awareness. April is Prevention of Animal Cruelty Month. JCHS Humane Operations has saved 195 pets in need from Jan 2019 through April 2020! Celebrate those that NOW have a voice, but remember those that still do not.
Join us on April 30th at 6pm on our Facebook page for a special video with our Humane Agent, followed by a moment of silence. Share your candle photos all over Facebook and use the hashtag #shareyourlight so your candles can be used for the vigil.
TOGETHER, MAKING A DIFFERENCE!

shared_text:
Edison Local Schools
April 27 at 3:29 PM ·

Lori Haught is the April Employee of the Month!

Lori has been in the Edison district on and off for 15 years. For the last 3 years, she has been in the EHS kitchen.

Lori was a Stanton High School graduate and all 3 of her sons graduated from Edison High School.

Lori enjoys reading, shopping, and spending time with my family.

Lori and her fellow foodservice co-workers have been hard at work during the school shut down making sure that our students do not go hungry while they cannot get to school. The food service department, with help from other employees and the community, has been serving breakfast and lunch to our students every Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday since the shut down began!

Congratulations, Lori!

The Edison Local School District is a participant district in Ohio’s Early Literacy Pilot. For the past three years, all teachers in grades Pre-K-3rd have gone through intensive professional learning on the science of reading utilizing LETRS (Language Essentials for Teachers of Reading and Spelling). The teachers are providing explicit instructional practices based on the science of reading. With the school closure continuing for the remainder of the school year, the district would like to provide some tutorial videos to assist parents/caregivers with some strategies that are aligned with the science of reading. These short videos will provide parents/caregivers with a short explanation of the strategy as well as modeling of what the strategy looks like in practice.

The first video, titled Tap It-Map It, is a strategy designed to build the basic phonemic awareness skills of segmenting and blending.

https://youtu.be/89Z-TkmrMp8

post_text:
Wednesday Wellness Challenge challenge is simple: find five people in your life and check-in with them every day for the next 30-days.

Ohio's Strive for Five Challenge is a new, statewide awareness campaign to help individuals and families cope with feelings of stress, anxiety, and isolation by connecting with others.

You are encouraged to reach out, connect, and comfort each other while we all work our way through the COVID-19 crisis and social distancing. Peer-to-peer support has great power in helping to calm anxiety and fear. By reaching out via phone, text, email, or even a hand-written note, you can help.

The Strive for Five Challenge was developed by the New York Coalition for Behavioral Health and brought to Ohio by the Mental Health, Addiction and Recovery Services Board of Lorain County.

Your weekly Wednesday Wellness Challenge from your School Counselors, Mrs. Pepperling & Ms. McGee:

#InThisTogether Challenge
Social distancing can change how you usually interact with people you care about. We want to help you consider how to build community and support systems, while we are all stuck at home.

Some ways you can connect virtually with friends, family, teachers, and your community:

Plan virtual dinners and coffee breaks; do at-home crafts and activities over a video call; watch a virtual concert together; read the same book or watch the same movie/TV show and talk about it; play online multiplayer video games; or join an online exercise class!

Go to edisonwildcats.org/guidance for more information and a video!

Post in the comments or on Twitter with the hashtag #InThisTogether and show us how you are staying connected with your communities.

Every night for the next 44 nights there will be a 15 minute online concert from 7:00-7:15 on Facebook live as a part of the Sycamore Sings “Songs of Hope” Online Concert Series. The lineup is unbelievable and the artists will perform a wide variety of music such as Gospel, Country, Bluegrass, Pop, Instrumental and more! We have nationally known artists as well as stellar young local talent all pitching in to uplift our community. Tune in for the first one tonight at 7:00 and keep this calendar handy for future reference.

post_text:
From your EHS counselors, Mrs. Pepperling and Ms. McGee:
Starting today, we will be posting weekly Wednesday Wellness messages here and on our website (edisonwildcats.org/guidance).
This week’s topic is Be Present. During these times of uncertainty, fear, and worry about our future, it can be difficult to slow down, listen, focus, and Be Present in the here and now.
Here are 5 tips to practice Being Present:
1. Breathing exercises
2. Meditation or yoga
3. Progressive muscle relaxation or stretching
4. Turn of your devices and ‘disconnect’
5. Give a friend or family member 100% of your attention

We want to challenge you all to post a picture and short message about what you choose to do to Be Present! EHS staff, students, and parents, post on twitter or below using the hashtag #wildcatway”

Yesterday’s update from Mr. Beattie is below. Obviously with the Governor’s extension of the school closure, more information will be forthcoming!

Good Evening. This is our weekly update as we enter week three of our mandatory school closure.

This week's lunch schedule will have a slight adjustment. The days will continue to be Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday, but some delivery times will be different.

The following sites will remain the same with meal availability being from 10:30 to 11:30. Hilltop Church, Irondale Methodist, Amsterdam Church of God and Empire Methodist.

The revision to delivery times for all other sites will be as follows. 10:30 to 11:00, Pleasant Hill Trailer Court, New Somerset Christian Church, Bergholz Trinity United Presbytarian and Smitty's Old School. Delivery times for Lake Lodge Trailer Court and East Springfield Church of God will be from 11:15 to 11:45.

Please visit our website and facebook for changes.

As always, please stay safe and healthy as we continue through these unprecedented times.

post_text:
Today is World Down Syndrome Day! Lanie Warren and her friends planned to celebrate and spread awareness at school on Friday, but since that was cancelled her brothers had to stand in!

World Down Syndrome Day is marked each year on March 21, beginning in 2006. The 21st day of March (the 3rd month of the year) was selected to signify the uniqueness of the triplication (trisomy) of the 21st chromosome which causes Down syndrome.
